CHAPTER 6: CONSEQUENCES
VINCENT
The office is dark except for the desk lamp.
3 AM. Most of Los Angeles is sleeping. I'm not.
Marcus Delgado sits across from me. His hands are zip-tied behind the chair. He's sweating. Good. He should be.
"Tell me what happened," I say.
My voice is calm. I've learned over twenty years that calm is more terrifying than shouting. Shouting means you've lost control. Calm means you never had to find it.
"Three people," Delgado stammers. "Masked. Professional. They knew what they were looking for."
"And your security?"
"Five men. All down. Broken bones, gunshot wounds. Non-lethal." He's talking fast now, desperate. "But they were GOOD, Mr. Harlan. Military-grade equipment. Suppressed weapons. They moved like—"
"Like they knew what they were doing."
"Yes, sir."
I stand. Walk around my desk. Delgado's eyes follow me. Prey tracking a predator.
"So you're telling me," I say quietly, "that three people walked into your storage unit, defeated five armed men, cracked your safe in under a minute, and took everything. And twelve hours later, you still have no idea who they were."
"We're pulling surveillance footage from—"
"Twelve hours, Marcus."
He goes quiet.
I pull a knife from my desk drawer. Not a gun. Guns are loud. Impersonal. Distance weapons. A knife requires commitment.
"Twenty years," I say, testing the edge with my thumb. "I've been building this empire for twenty years. Carefully. Methodically. And you lost me records that could expose six shell companies, fourteen properties, and three city councilmembers. Do you understand what that means?"
"Please," Delgado whispers. "I can fix this. I can find them. I'll—"
"No, Marcus. You can't."
I move fast. The knife goes in below his ribs, angled up. Quick. Clean. He makes a sound—half gasp, half moan. I hold him there for five seconds while his eyes go wide, then wider, then empty.
I pull the knife out. Wipe it on his jacket. Sit back down at my desk.
Press the intercom. "Clean this up."
Two men appear within thirty seconds. Efficient. Professional. They don't ask questions. That's why I pay them.
While they work, I make a call.
"Sir?" My head of security. Always awake. Always ready.
"I want everyone who's worked on my properties in the last year. Every contractor, every property manager, every courier. Names, addresses, employment records."
"All of them, sir?"
"All of them. And I want three bodies by sunrise."
Silence. Then: "Which three, sir?"
"I don't care. People who MIGHT be involved. People who have access. Make them examples."
"Understood."
I hang up. Make two more calls. Same instructions. Different targets.
By the time the sun rises, three men will be dead. And everyone else who's ever worked for me will know: you touch my operations, everyone you know dies.
Fear is a tool.
Right now, whoever did this thinks they're smart. Thinks they got away clean.
By morning, they'll realize they're hunted.
I pour myself coffee. Watch the city lights through my window. Los Angeles spread out below me like a chessboard.
Someone just made a move.
Now it's my turn.

COLE
The TV in the safehouse is on low. Background noise while I work.
7 AM. I've been up all night going through Delgado's files. Property records. Shell companies. Tenant complaints. The paper trail of Vincent's empire.
One file stops me cold.
Tenant complaint letters from 4247 South Boyle Avenue. Mat's building.
Heat not working for three weeks. Children are getting sick.
Rent increased 15% with no notice. Cannot afford. Please reconsider.
Eviction notice received. We have nowhere to go.
I processed this building four years ago. Made the purchase look legitimate. Inflated appraisal. Clean paperwork. Vincent Harlan bought it with laundered cartel money and I made it look like a routine real estate investment.
And now families are suffering because I was good at my job.
I light a cigarette. Stare at the complaints.
My phone buzzes. Ignored call from Jennifer at the office. Three emails about property closings. A text from Vincent's lawyer about next week's transactions.
The world doesn't stop just because I'm planning a rebellion.
The TV suddenly goes LOUD. Breaking news jingle.
"—reporting three bodies discovered across Los Angeles early this morning. Police say all three victims appear to be execution-style killings—"
I look up.
Three photos on the screen.
Miguel Santos. Property manager. Echo Park. Shot in his car.
David Chen. Contractor. Koreatown. Home invasion.
Robert Wade. Courier. South LA. Found in an alley.
The reporter continues: "Sources say all three victims had ties to real estate operations in the area. Police are investigating possible connections to organized crime—"
My stomach drops.
I know these names.
Santos managed eight buildings for one of Vincent's shell companies. I processed his employment paperwork two years ago.
Chen did renovations on Vincent's properties. Inflated invoices I made look legitimate.
Wade moved cash between locations. I never met him, but his name's in the files.
They had nothing to do with the Delgado job.
Vincent's killing everyone who MIGHT be involved.
My phone's in my hand. Text to Ray and Mat: Turn on the news. We need to meet. Now.
I stare at the screen. Three dead men.
I didn't pull the trigger.
But I built the system that put them in the crosshairs.

MAT
The kitchen smells like eggs and coffee.
Normal. Too normal.
Ma's at the stove, cooking breakfast before her shift at the office building downtown. Isa's at the table, textbook open, highlighting something. Saturday morning routine. Like nothing's changed.
But everything's changed.
I've barely slept. Keep seeing last night—the fight, the blood, Ray's confession, the gun in my hand aimed at his chest.
My phone's on silent in my pocket. The duffel bag of money is hidden under my bed. Fifteen thousand dollars that could pay six months of rent and Ma's insulin for a year.
Blood money.
"Mateo, you want eggs?" Ma doesn't turn around.
"No, Ma. I'm good."
"You look tired, mijo. (Son.) You okay?"
"Yeah. Just didn't sleep well."
Isa looks up from her book. Studies me. She KNOWS something's wrong. Can see it in my face.
"You sure?" she asks quietly.
"I'm sure."
Ma plates her eggs, kisses my forehead on her way out. "Be good. Love you."
"Love you too, Ma."
The door closes. Isa and I sit in silence for exactly five seconds.
"What did you do?"
"Nothing."
"Mat." She closes her book. "You came home at 4 AM. You look like you haven't slept in days. And you keep checking your phone like someone's chasing you. What. Did. You. Do?"
I can't tell her. Can't explain that I robbed someone last night. That I worked with two strangers to fight five armed men. That one of those strangers watched my father get killed and did nothing.
"I'm handling it, Isa."
"That's not an answer."
My phone buzzes. I pull it out—Cisco.
Fuck.
I stand. "I gotta go."
"Mat—"
I'm already heading for the door. Answer the call outside.
"Qué pedo." (What's up.)
"Hermano." Cisco's voice is ice. "You see the news?"
"What news?"
"Turn on your TV. Channel Seven."
I pull up the news on my phone. Three bodies. Execution-style. All connected to real estate.
My blood goes cold.
"That's Vincent Harlan's territory," Cisco says. "Three of his people. Dead. And YOU hit one of his property managers two nights ago."
"So?"
"So people are DYING, Mat. And I need to know—are these guys you're working with starting a war?"
I don't answer. Can't answer.
"Because if they are," Cisco continues, "my neighborhood's in the crosshairs. My PEOPLE are in the crosshairs. And I need to know if you're with me or against me."
"I'm not against you, hermano."
"Then PROVE it. Tonight. Midnight. The spot. You, me, and whoever the fuck you're working with. Face to face. Or we got a problem."
He hangs up.
I stand outside my building. Morning sun. People going to work. Kids playing in the street.
Normal. All of it so fucking normal.
And I'm in the middle of a war I barely understand.
My phone buzzes again. Text from Cole: Turn on the news. We need to meet. Now.

RAY
The TV's on. Has been all night.
I'm sitting on my couch. Bottle of whiskey on the coffee table. Unopened.
Three days sober.
Seventy-two hours since I stood in that bar and decided maybe, maybe I could be something other than a drunk waiting to die.
The news shows three bodies. Three men executed. All connected to Vincent Harlan's operations.
I know this pattern.
Saw it during my undercover days. Vincent doesn't retaliate against the people who hit him—he retaliates against everyone who MIGHT be connected. Burns the whole network to find the leak.
Effective. Brutal. Terrifying.
And now three more people are dead because I, Cole, and Mat hit Delgado.
My hands are shaking. Withdrawal. Three days without alcohol and my body's screaming for it.
I stare at the bottle.
Just one drink. Just to stop the shaking.
Ricardo Navarro's face flashes in my mind. Traffic stop. Eight years ago. My partner's gun going off six times. Ricardo falling. Me standing there. Doing nothing.
Mat's face at Griffith Park. The gun pointed at my chest. You watched them kill my father.
Now three more faces on the TV. Three more people dead because I wasn't strong enough to say no. Wasn't strong enough to fight back when it mattered.
I pick up the bottle.
Hold it.
Feel the weight.
My phone buzzes. Cole's text: Turn on the news. We need to meet. Now.
I look at the TV. At the bodies. At the bottle.
Three days sober.
Three days trying to be something other than a coward.
And the world's already burning.
I set the bottle down.
Not because I'm strong.
Because if I drink now, Mat was right. I'm just a coward who watched people die and did nothing.
I can't be that anymore.
Even if it kills me.

CISCO
The corner store on 38th Street is mine.
Not legally. But everyone knows. I protect it. The owner pays me. Fair trade.
My crew's inside. Five guys. All young. All hungry. All looking at me for answers.
Because three bodies dropped last night and everyone's nervous.
"Ese," Flaco says. He's nineteen. Good kid. "If Harlan's hunting someone in our territory, we need to be ready."
"We're always ready."
"I'm serious, man. Three bodies in one night. That's a message." Memo, older, smarter. "And word is one of those dead guys worked out of a building two blocks from here."
I lean against the counter. Process this.
Vincent Harlan.
I've never met him. Don't want to. But I know the name. Everyone does. The Broker. The man who owns half of LA and makes problems disappear.
If he thinks someone in MY territory hit him?
My people are in danger.
"Find out everything you can," I tell them. "Who got hit. Where. When. I want to know if this touches us."
They nod. Start making calls.
I step outside. Light a cigarette.
Pull out my phone. Scroll to old photos. Me and Mat. Twelve years old. Playing ball in the park. Big smiles. Brothers.
I let him stay clean because of that. Because he was smart. Because he could be something I never could.
But two nights ago he hit a storage unit. Worked with two guys I've never met. Got into something he won't explain.
And now bodies are dropping.
Brotherhood ends where survival begins.
My phone rings. One of my guys calling from his cousin who works dispatch.
"Cisco. Those three bodies? All Vincent Harlan's people. Property managers, contractors, couriers. Someone hit his network."
"Anyone claiming it?"
"No one. But word is Harlan's hunting. Killing everyone who might know something."
I hang up.
Stare at Mat's building across the street.
He's in over his head.
And I need to know if I'm pulling him out or putting him down.

COLE
Noon. We're all at the safehouse.
Mat arrives first. Tense. Wired.
Ray second. Hands shaking. Looks like he's barely holding it together.
I spread today's newspaper on the table. Three photos. Three bodies.
"Vincent killed three people last night," I say. "None of them had anything to do with us."
"He's burning everyone to find us," Ray says quietly.
Mat's staring at the photos. "Cisco knows something's up. He's asking questions. Wants to meet tonight. Me, you two, face to face."
"We're not meeting Cisco."
"We don't have a choice." Mat's voice is hard. "He controls my neighborhood. If he decides I'm a threat, my family's caught in the middle."
Ray leans forward. "Then you're dead."
"Exactly."
Silence.
I light a cigarette. "Vincent will keep killing until someone talks or until he finds us. Which means we have two options. Run. Or accelerate."
"Accelerate?" Mat looks at me like I'm insane.
"We hit him again. Bigger target. More damage. Before he finds us."
Ray stands up. "That's fucking insane. We hit him AGAIN and more people die."
"People are ALREADY dying." I point at the newspaper. "At least if we keep hitting him, we're working toward something."
"Three people are DEAD, Cole. Because of what we did."
"And three MORE will die tomorrow. And three more the day after. Vincent doesn't stop. So we either run and let him keep killing. Or we fight and make it count."
Ray's hands are shaking worse now. Sweating. He looks like he's about to explode or collapse.
"You good?" Mat asks him.
"I'm fine."
"You don't look fine."
"I SAID I'm fine." Ray's voice cracks. "What's the next target?"
I pull out the file I've been working on since 4 AM.
"Senator Richard Castellano. Vincent's puppet. Been in his pocket for eight years. He's hosting a campaign fundraiser Friday night at La Mer in West Hollywood."
"That's one of Vincent's restaurants," Ray says.
"Exactly. High-end French place. Vincent owns it through a shell company. Castellano's fundraiser is half a million in campaign donations. All dirty money Vincent's laundering through political contributions."
Mat crosses his arms. "We rob a senator? In public? At a restaurant full of rich people and security?"
"We rob the money Vincent's using to buy politicians. And we do it in front of everyone."
"That's suicide."
"That's the POINT." I tap the file. "Vincent thinks we're small-time. Street-level criminals who got lucky with Delgado. We hit something THIS big, THIS public? It sends a message."
"What message?" Mat asks. "That we're fucking idiots?"
"That we're not scared." I look at both of them. "Vincent's hunting us. Burning the city to find us. So we walk into his restaurant, rob his senator, and walk out. Show him we're not hiding."
Ray's quiet. Too quiet.
"Ray?" I say.
"I'm in." His voice is flat. Dead. "When do we start planning?"
"Monday. We've got five days to scout, plan, and execute."
Mat shakes his head. "This is insane."
"You have a better idea?"
Long silence.
"What about Cisco?" Mat asks finally.
"Stall him. Tell him you need more time. We can't deal with him AND plan this."
"He gave me until tonight."
"Then lie. You're good at infiltration. Be good at lying too."
Mat doesn't look happy. But he nods.
The meeting breaks up. Mat leaves first. Ray second.
I'm alone with the files. The photos of the dead men. The map of Vincent's empire.
Three bodies in one night.
And that's just the beginning.
Vincent's going to burn this city to find us.
So we better burn him first.
The TV's still on in the corner. News at noon.
"—authorities investigating what appears to be an escalating gang war. Three dead, dozens more missing. Residents are advised to remain vigilant. Los Angeles Police Chief issued a statement saying—"
I turn it off.
Sit in silence.
Three broken people trying to take down an empire.
And the body count's already started.
